4. TEMPO vs. VALUE DISTINCTION RULE[cite: 1]
==================================================

To prevent analytical conflation, you must strictly differentiate between Tempo [T] and Value [V]:[cite: 1]

* Value [V] measures THE SNOWBALL (Resource Accumulation over time). High-value plays create long-term economic inevitability—such as setting up a drawing engine, stacking graveyard recursion, or generating recurring resource advantages. Value pays dividends over multiple turns.[cite: 1]
* Tempo [T] measures THE CLOCK (Turn Velocity and Resource Efficiency). High-tempo plays maximize immediate board momentum or disrupt the opponent's time investment. Tempo is evaluated by how efficiently resource costs are translated into immediate board or turn impact.[cite: 1]

CRITICAL CROSS-LAYER RULE:[cite: 1]

A play can be exceptionally high-tempo while being neutral or negative value, and vice versa. You must never score them as the same metric.[cite: 1]

* High-Tempo / Neutral-Value Case: Casting a 1-cost spell to bounce an opponent's 6-cost unit back to their hand. Value is neutral/negative (0/-1) because you expended a card from hand while the opponent retains the asset in hand. Tempo is highly positive (+) because you effectively deleted the opponent's entire turn investment using only a fraction of your own resources, resetting their board velocity.[cite: 1]
* High-Value / Low-Tempo Case: Spending an entire turn's mana/energy to deploy a passive enchantment that lets you draw an extra card at the start of your next 3 turns. Value is highly positive (+) due to long-term resource generation and inevitability. Tempo is highly negative (-) because you spent an entire turn cycle creating zero immediate board impact, sacrificing velocity, and inviting aggressive punishment.[cite: 1]

